00:12:51.240 --> 00:12:53.400
Sailors and Daughters first
began with the concern

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:56.820
to feature this early
photography from East Africa coming

00:12:56.820 --> 00:12:59.920
from the archive and from the
library collections at the museum.

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:02.140
And from there it grew
very, very quickly.

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:04.750
We realized, you know, the
possibilities were much bigger

00:13:04.750 --> 00:13:06.720
than what was there
at the Smithsonian,

00:13:06.720 --> 00:13:12.190
even with Sackler Freer, and
on the other hand, you know,

00:13:12.190 --> 00:13:15.800
while we have very little
documentation of this area so far,

00:13:15.800 --> 00:13:19.790
there was so much material that
signaled a really colonial point

00:13:19.790 --> 00:13:21.610
of view and we really
wanted to disturb

00:13:21.610 --> 00:13:25.280
and upset those kinds
of image fictions.

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:28.970 position:56%
And so the challenge became how to
do this for photographic collections

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:32.600
that predominantly featured
commercial and touristic kinds

00:13:32.600 --> 00:13:37.030
of imagery, so this map
really kind of, you know,

00:13:37.030 --> 00:13:39.510
gives us a large perspective of
when we are starting to think

00:13:39.510 --> 00:13:42.090
about things not in
terms of territoriality,

00:13:42.090 --> 00:13:45.830
but in terms of connections and
the Indian Ocean as connecting all

00:13:45.830 --> 00:13:47.130
of these different points of view.

00:13:47.130 --> 00:13:52.310
And probably viewed by the cultural
exchange, the artistic exchange,

00:13:52.310 --> 00:13:54.890
and the exchange of people,
ideas, and technologies

00:13:54.890 --> 00:13:56.560
through the Indian Ocean.

00:13:56.560 --> 00:13:59.390
Not over the two centuries, you
know, in which this work comes

00:13:59.390 --> 00:14:03.520
from that really over the
millennia answered of trying

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:08.630
to draw attention to
that sort of thing.

00:14:08.630 --> 00:14:10.750
When we were learning about
their early photographers

00:14:10.750 --> 00:14:13.160
who were working in this region.

00:14:13.160 --> 00:14:15.550
You know, we wanted to find out -

00:14:15.550 --> 00:14:18.100
what we found out resonates
very much with what happens

00:14:18.100 --> 00:14:19.700
in other parts of the world.

00:14:19.700 --> 00:14:22.520
And that is that early
photography in East Africa

00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:26.030
and a larger Indian Ocean
are resolutely the products

00:14:26.030 --> 00:14:28.840
and imperatives of
movement and migration.

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:32.360
And it was the mobility of
photographers and the wider realm

00:14:32.360 --> 00:14:36.540
of their audiences that situates
these photographic modernities,

00:14:36.540 --> 00:14:39.040
really from the 1870's on.

00:14:39.040 --> 00:14:42.410
So these photographs are the
creative collaborations I would

00:14:42.410 --> 00:14:47.940 position:56%
argue between photographers, between
their subjects, their patrons

00:14:47.940 --> 00:14:52.790 position:56%
and us and, you know, future viewers
to come to sort of global audiences

00:14:52.790 --> 00:14:54.440
that we see happening now.

00:14:54.440 --> 00:14:55.740
And as such they really fold

00:14:55.740 --> 00:15:00.940
in across a vast photographic
and cultural space.

00:15:00.940 --> 00:15:05.030
Sailors and Daughters evoke that
fundamental premise of movement

00:15:05.030 --> 00:15:10.110
of ideas and people and so
we will see a lot of that.

