in that very dense city, in the
very wealthy city of Stone Town.

00:16:51.480 --> 00:16:56.470
So just trying to sort of alert
us to this sort of neighborhoods

00:16:56.470 --> 00:17:01.690
as they were mapped and tracked
there before everything changed.

00:17:01.690 --> 00:17:06.020
So we see - hold on.

00:17:06.020 --> 00:17:10.970
So we see here Bitell Hakoom
[phonic] part of the palace complex

00:17:10.970 --> 00:17:12.380
of the Sultan of Zanzibar.

00:17:12.380 --> 00:17:18.050 position:56%
So the sultans, especially in
1870's, he was a massive modernizer.

00:17:18.050 --> 00:17:21.000
He commissioned lots and
lots of architecture,

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.430
a huge new palace complex.

00:17:23.430 --> 00:17:28.480
And, you know, was really known
for trying to bring Zanzibar into,

00:17:28.480 --> 00:17:31.840
you know, the very, very modern
era and he was really proud of all

00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:34.950
of the commissions that he had.

00:17:34.950 --> 00:17:39.730
Here's one of the early - these
are a couple of different guys, HH,

00:17:39.730 --> 00:17:44.680
his highness Sultan Sayed
Survagosh Dinsyed [phonic].

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:48.950
This is around 1880 and we can see,
you know, again people traveling.

00:17:48.950 --> 00:17:52.620
This is a great portrait
I'm taken in London

00:17:52.620 --> 00:17:54.870 position:56%
and then a bit later closer to 1902.

00:17:54.870 --> 00:17:58.660
The Sultan Sayed [inaudible]
Mohammed Bin Sayed

00:17:58.660 --> 00:18:02.890
and this is around 1902.

00:18:02.890 --> 00:18:05.410
So we see lots of images
like this throughout.

00:18:05.410 --> 00:18:10.160
And I'm trying to give a sense
of the urban infrastructure

00:18:10.160 --> 00:18:13.760
that may be really surprising for
people who haven't seen, you know,

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:18.320
that East Coast urban build up
and the extraordinary wealth

00:18:18.320 --> 00:18:21.640
of that mercantile
economy that existed there.

00:18:21.640 --> 00:18:26.690
And then the people who were, you
know, who made it all possible.

00:18:26.690 --> 00:18:31.910 position:56%
And the people who were the laborers
and, you know after the abolition

00:18:31.910 --> 00:18:35.160
of slavery in the 1890's
were the people

00:18:35.160 --> 00:18:39.610
who manage the clove plantations
and had been brought not only

00:18:39.610 --> 00:18:43.260
from the East African mainland,
but also from, you know,

00:18:43.260 --> 00:18:45.360
as far north as Ethiopia.

00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:48.380
People had come from India, of
course, with the great migrations

00:18:48.380 --> 00:18:50.060
that had come from Western India.

00:18:50.060 --> 00:18:53.630
People were really coming
from all over the place.

