00:19:02.750 --> 00:19:05.310
and we can see that
mapped in Zanzibar.

00:19:05.310 --> 00:19:10.640
He was, you know, responsible for
so much of the migration of people

00:19:12.030 --> 00:19:17.410
as commodities really across to the
Indian Ocean and through the Gulf.

00:19:17.410 --> 00:19:21.040
And then on the other side of
Umgumbo [phonic] we see people who,

00:19:21.040 --> 00:19:24.590
you know, the infrastructure
and the layout of the land

00:19:24.590 --> 00:19:26.950
and how people are living
is of course quite different

00:19:26.950 --> 00:19:31.720 position:56%
and it's very, very rare to actually
see images like this of, you know,

00:19:31.720 --> 00:19:34.310
people living and sort of
going about their daily lives

00:19:34.310 --> 00:19:39.420
when they weren't working in,
you know, out on the plantations.

00:19:39.420 --> 00:19:44.650
So we see, you know,
people like AC Gomez.

00:19:44.650 --> 00:19:48.370
A lot of the photographers
who started in Zanzibar

00:19:48.370 --> 00:19:53.050
and founded the first photo studios
were not only exploring Stone Town,

00:19:53.050 --> 00:19:55.760
but they were going to
Umgumbo, going to the other side

00:19:55.760 --> 00:19:57.670
and really exploring the
whole countryside and it's

00:19:57.670 --> 00:20:03.020
through their photographs that
we have a sense of what Zanzibar

00:20:03.020 --> 00:20:05.350
in the area look like,
really from the 1870's.

00:20:05.350 --> 00:20:11.550
You know, we have that happen in
Zanzibar, in Mombasa, in Aiden,

00:20:11.550 --> 00:20:15.520
you know, all over the place
and there remains much more work

00:20:15.520 --> 00:20:17.650
to be done on those photographers.

00:20:17.650 --> 00:20:20.030
So we're trying to piece
together really there

00:20:20.030 --> 00:20:22.270
and it's very, very tricky.

00:20:22.270 --> 00:20:26.690
And again with the problem that
we see with a lot of histories,

00:20:26.690 --> 00:20:29.600
creative histories in Africa
is where are the archives?

00:20:29.600 --> 00:20:32.500
Where are the repositories
of these photographs?

00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:37.990
And so this is the trick, right.

00:20:37.990 --> 00:20:46.940
We'll move on to [inaudible] who
was an explorer who is moving

00:20:46.940 --> 00:20:50.160
through the North African coast
and down the Swahili coast in the,

00:20:50.160 --> 00:20:54.100
you know to sort of
map out strategic ports

00:20:54.100 --> 00:20:57.790
in French holdings along the
Indian Ocean in the 1840's.

00:20:57.790 --> 00:20:59.960
So right at the start
of the, you know,

00:20:59.960 --> 00:21:01.740
the sort of birth of photography.

00:21:01.740 --> 00:21:06.110 position:56%
And as he moved, you know, he had
his ships and he had a daguerreotype

00:21:06.110 --> 00:21:10.180
