00:21:21.650 --> 00:21:26.570
that were made in East Africa
and they were bound in this book

00:21:26.570 --> 00:21:28.600
that he made this Voyage
[foreign language].

00:21:28.600 --> 00:21:33.340 position:56%
The book is actually about this big.

00:21:33.340 --> 00:21:34.640
It's huge.

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:36.890
It's down there at the
Library of Congress or sorry,

00:21:36.890 --> 00:21:40.380
down at the Warner Robins
Library down at the Smithsonian.

00:21:40.380 --> 00:21:44.050
It's about this tall, sort
of this wide and this long,

00:21:44.050 --> 00:21:47.980
so the technological difficulty
of trying to make the scans

00:21:47.980 --> 00:21:50.190
and then trying to figure out
a way to make that accessible

00:21:50.190 --> 00:21:54.100
and disseminated on a website that
people could look at on their phone

00:21:54.100 --> 00:21:56.610
in Nairobi was really,
really a trick.

00:21:56.610 --> 00:21:58.820
And so we tried to manage it.

00:21:58.820 --> 00:22:00.920
There's a huge amount
of information there.

00:22:00.920 --> 00:22:02.890
I mean I really strongly
encourage everybody

00:22:02.890 --> 00:22:04.420
to sort of flip through these.

00:22:04.420 --> 00:22:07.590
We have a selection
of those images there.

00:22:07.590 --> 00:22:11.900
You know it was really a priority
for us to be able to disseminate

00:22:11.900 --> 00:22:14.740
that and these images
are very compelling to me

00:22:14.740 --> 00:22:17.950
because they reveal the diversity
of people who were coming

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:20.770
from central Africa and
East Africa and then living

00:22:20.770 --> 00:22:22.420
on those coastal cities,

00:22:22.420 --> 00:22:26.770
such as [inaudible]
Mogadishu, Zanzibar and Mombasa.

00:22:26.770 --> 00:22:29.610
So we see them in the cities
that they were living in and some

00:22:29.610 --> 00:22:31.960
of the prominent traders,
which of course were the people

00:22:31.960 --> 00:22:33.670
that Geelem [phonic]
was coming in contact

00:22:33.670 --> 00:22:36.750
with because that was his mission.

00:22:36.750 --> 00:22:40.380
You know, along the coast of
East Africa and further afield.

00:22:40.380 --> 00:22:44.380
What we see with this
one is Swahili family

00:22:44.380 --> 00:22:49.010
and of course we can see
these are lithographs based

00:22:49.010 --> 00:22:50.310
on the daguerreotypes
that are there.

00:22:50.310 --> 00:22:52.730
These are not of course the
original daguerreotypes.

00:22:52.730 --> 00:22:55.060
We haven't found those yet.

00:22:55.060 --> 00:22:56.410
I'm not sure that they exist.

00:22:56.410 --> 00:22:59.700 position:56%
It's often the case that they don't.

00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:02.520
The rules of - you know,
the other thing that I

00:23:02.520 --> 00:23:06.600
like about these portraits, their
complexity they really force us

00:23:06.600 --> 00:23:10.240
to look hard, especially when
we deal with Geelem's text,

00:23:10.240 --> 00:23:13.070
which is which is also
there in these huge volumes

00:23:13.070 --> 00:23:16.670
and which has been written about
my colleague a little bit Zavia

00:23:16.670 --> 00:23:18.810
Korvubla [phonic], which
is available on our site.

00:23:18.810 --> 00:23:20.870
I can show that to you.

00:23:20.870 --> 00:23:26.750
As portraits they initially appear
to be intimate and respectful.

00:23:26.750 --> 00:23:29.150
I suspect actually that the moment

00:23:29.150 --> 00:23:33.270
of photographic encounter was
far more ambiguous and fraught.

00:23:33.270 --> 00:23:38.050
Geelem convinced Swahili
translators, negotiators, traders,

00:23:38.050 --> 00:23:41.040
and their families to sit for
the camera, which they had to sit

00:23:41.040 --> 00:23:42.590
for a long time, we'll remember.

00:23:42.590 --> 00:23:44.720
And he wrote about those
moments and how they were

00:23:44.720 --> 00:23:49.030
so widely observed by
curious bystanders.

00:23:49.030 --> 00:23:52.480
And, you know, as probably
many of you are aware the rules

00:23:52.480 --> 00:23:55.700
of Muslim modesty restricted
Geelem's access

00:23:55.700 --> 00:23:57.890
and his conversations with women.

00:23:57.890 --> 00:24:01.090
And so it was their husbands
and in some cases their masters,

00:24:01.090 --> 00:24:07.340
the people who owned them who
compels some of the depicted women

00:24:07.340 --> 00:24:09.630
and servants to sit for Geelem.

00:24:09.630 --> 00:24:14.390
So we see all the complexities of
status and the senses of looking

00:24:14.390 --> 00:24:16.760
at that are sort of going on here.

00:24:16.760 --> 00:24:21.560
So in this case we have these
portraits of the small girl

00:24:21.560 --> 00:24:25.810
on the left - sorry, on the
bottom center is actually niece

00:24:25.810 --> 00:24:27.110
of the governor.

00:24:27.110 --> 00:24:30.230
Her name is or was Aziza
and she's completely ducked

00:24:30.230 --> 00:24:33.500
out for her portrait to,
you know, all of the jewels,

00:24:33.500 --> 00:24:36.010
everything has been
sort of laid upon her.

00:24:36.010 --> 00:24:41.010
She's been completely adorned
for this photographic moment

00:24:41.010 --> 00:24:45.190
and it was watching that process
of the creation of her portrait

00:24:45.190 --> 00:24:48.090
that convinced the governor
eventually to sit for Geelem.

00:24:48.090 --> 00:24:52.060
So we have these little moments
of, you know, really interesting

00:24:52.060 --> 00:24:53.880
and provocative interaction

00:24:53.880 --> 00:24:58.060
that this is really only
the tip of the iceberg for.

00:24:58.060 --> 00:25:03.030
I'll just briefly note
Zavia Korvubla's research,

00:25:03.030 --> 00:25:06.130
because the text is in French
and we really have, you know,

00:25:06.130 --> 00:25:10.720
as we know a lot of them
difficulty addressing those text,

00:25:10.720 --> 00:25:13.560
especially as Americans and really
getting them to be accessible

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:15.310
in a variety of languages.

00:25:15.310 --> 00:25:18.330
So he put them up the
bit that he studied

00:25:18.330 --> 00:25:20.810
and they're really
intriguing accounts

00:25:20.810 --> 00:25:24.610
and I highly recommend you go
to them on the unbound Web site,

00:25:24.610 --> 00:25:28.300
the library and Smithsonian
website there.

00:25:28.300 --> 00:25:31.810
And we see the variety
of people that are there.

00:25:31.810 --> 00:25:35.160
There are people who are slaves,
people who have been, you know,

00:25:35.160 --> 00:25:38.340
compelled to sit, and then we have
people of course who, you know,

00:25:38.340 --> 00:25:41.030
look modern and we imagine
there's a big difference

00:25:41.030 --> 00:25:43.380
and a big cultural
divide between them.

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:45.880
But of course these interactions
were happening all of the time

00:25:45.880 --> 00:25:49.060
and exchanges were happening all
of the time and he was just sort

00:25:49.060 --> 00:25:55.050 position:56%
of there to make it happen in some
ways, but also witnessing, you know,

00:25:55.050 --> 00:25:56.710
what was in front of him.

00:25:56.710 --> 00:25:59.530 position:56%
I had a student recently, a Somalian
American student who's really

00:25:59.530 --> 00:26:02.270
concerned about these images
and she had a lot of questions

00:26:02.270 --> 00:26:06.900
about the anionic mandate and the
questions of modesty and propriety.

00:26:06.900 --> 00:26:10.130
And it generated a lot of
conversation about the role

00:26:10.130 --> 00:26:12.940
of photography and who
were taking these pictures.

00:26:12.940 --> 00:26:17.280
And I pointed her, you know,
eventually - let me look -

00:26:17.280 --> 00:26:18.990
we can look at this
one really quickly.

00:26:18.990 --> 00:26:23.340
We see a really a sort
of probably a noblewoman

00:26:23.340 --> 00:26:25.810
or somebody who was very wealthy.

00:26:25.810 --> 00:26:31.610
She's wearing this sort of partial
mask called a [inaudible] related

00:26:31.610 --> 00:26:34.670
linguistically to the word for
burka, you know, the cover.

00:26:34.670 --> 00:26:36.560
And we see this come
up in photographs.

00:26:36.560 --> 00:26:40.240
It's something that was in favor
for a time in fashion and they kind

00:26:40.240 --> 00:26:42.330
of fell out of favor and a lot
of people have commented too

00:26:42.330 --> 00:26:44.140
on we don't see anything
like this anymore.

00:26:44.140 --> 00:26:46.580
But it is a very elaborate
sort of mask.

00:26:46.580 --> 00:26:49.930
But circling back,
I pointed my student

00:26:49.930 --> 00:26:54.740
to the great photography story of
Siddique Bay of Egypt, the guy who,

00:26:54.740 --> 00:26:58.900
you know, was an Egyptian
military officer

00:26:58.900 --> 00:27:03.950 position:56%
and who helped escort the huge
tapestry that was created every year

00:27:03.950 --> 00:27:08.280
in Cairo and then with a big
military possession every year took

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:12.080
it over at the covering
for the kava in Mecca

00:27:12.080 --> 00:27:14.970
and there was an extraordinary
sort of pilgrimage that happened.

00:27:14.970 --> 00:27:18.280
He was the one to take, from what
we know, the first photographs

00:27:18.280 --> 00:27:21.370 position:56%
of the kava and he didn't only do
that, but of course he took pictures

00:27:21.370 --> 00:27:24.360
of the pilgrimage sites, of
the people who were responsible

00:27:24.360 --> 00:27:26.420
for the [inaudible] and
different places there.

00:27:26.420 --> 00:27:31.440
So the question of how Muslim
photographers were negotiating all

00:27:31.440 --> 00:27:36.690 position:56%
of that is really, you know, kind of
fraught in an individualistic sort

00:27:36.690 --> 00:27:39.880
of question with lots of
different grains to that history.

00:27:39.880 --> 00:27:42.070
He published and released
seven volumes.

00:27:42.070 --> 00:27:45.160
He won prizes in Venice for his
photography, so there's a lot

00:27:45.160 --> 00:27:47.730
of stuff that I feel like should
be household names we should know

00:27:47.730 --> 00:27:49.690
about this and we don't.

00:27:49.690 --> 00:27:53.280
So it's just kind of peeling
back the history that, you know,

00:27:53.280 --> 00:27:59.140
or just seem inaccessible to us.

00:27:59.140 --> 00:28:03.070
This is shifting to
sort of another page.

00:28:03.070 --> 00:28:08.890
The page about Oman [phonic]
the cultural center of caboose

00:28:08.890 --> 00:28:13.010
who is [inaudible] funded at this
project on a lot of terrific work

00:28:13.010 --> 00:28:16.390
at the National Museum
of African Art.

00:28:16.390 --> 00:28:21.170 position:56%
Very early imagery from Oman in
this case was taken by a German sort

00:28:21.170 --> 00:28:25.050
of traveler itinerant photographer
named Herman Burchart [phonic]

00:28:25.050 --> 00:28:26.550
and his work is in Berlin.

00:28:26.550 --> 00:28:29.070
They kindly loaned us some images

00:28:29.070 --> 00:28:32.590
so that we can see a
little bit of the sense.

00:28:32.590 --> 00:28:35.200
And his approach has
been explored and written

00:28:35.200 --> 00:28:36.590
about sort of in great detail.

00:28:36.590 --> 00:28:40.670
He just won a [inaudible], but, you
know, I highly recommend you look

00:28:40.670 --> 00:28:43.490
at them the few images
that are there.

00:28:43.490 --> 00:28:47.300
In Muscat and also
another city called Matra,

00:28:47.300 --> 00:28:50.650
which was actually bigger than
Muscat, another port city.

00:28:50.650 --> 00:28:56.630
You know, we have the fish market
here and the harbor in the city.

00:28:56.630 --> 00:29:02.350
This was taken around
what do we think?

00:29:02.350 --> 00:29:04.100
1904, right.

00:29:04.100 --> 00:29:06.270
And when you're looking at
this and then you go back

00:29:06.270 --> 00:29:12.090
to the Zanzibar images you see
the huge similarities, right,

00:29:12.090 --> 00:29:14.730
in between the fish market
and how it looked in Zanzibar

00:29:14.730 --> 00:29:16.030
and how it's looking there.

00:29:16.030 --> 00:29:19.150
Swahili, all of these different
languages were being spoken

00:29:19.150 --> 00:29:22.240
in very different places again
reminding us of the migration

00:29:22.240 --> 00:29:26.230
of people and the very cosmopolitan
sense of a lot of these, you know,

00:29:26.230 --> 00:29:29.810
very small cities where people were
going back and forth all the time.

00:29:29.810 --> 00:29:36.690 position:56%
And it wasn't just a sort of a
one-way direction, so we get a sense

00:29:36.690 --> 00:29:40.500
of the difficulties in his
photographing out on the streets,

00:29:40.500 --> 00:29:42.200
but also the fact that
he managed to do it

00:29:42.200 --> 00:29:44.800
and that they were kept is amazing.

00:29:44.800 --> 00:29:50.040
Another great series of work,
which I only could gesture to here

00:29:50.040 --> 00:29:54.390
on the Web site, are the works
that are coming from Persia

00:29:54.390 --> 00:30:00.050
of the famous photographer Antoine
Sevregene [phonic] who terrific

00:30:00.050 --> 00:30:05.470
and wonderful collections are
there at Sackler Freer of his work.

00:30:05.470 --> 00:30:09.320
He went around and took
a lot of photographs,

00:30:09.320 --> 00:30:14.900
including royal commissions
photographs of big royal events

00:30:14.900 --> 00:30:19.670
and sorry, holidays and things like
that by royal and noble families

00:30:19.670 --> 00:30:24.280
who of course had people
from East Africa working

00:30:24.280 --> 00:30:26.650
within their families.

00:30:26.650 --> 00:30:29.490
In this instance there
really was no word for slave.

00:30:29.490 --> 00:30:31.750
People will not say, "Oh,
those people were our slaves."

00:30:31.750 --> 00:30:33.730
They will say, "They were servants.

00:30:33.730 --> 00:30:35.170
They became part of our family."

00:30:35.170 --> 00:30:39.330
And indeed I also recommend
the New Your Public Library

00:30:39.330 --> 00:30:45.220
who did a larger exhibition, which
was sort of more encompassing

00:30:45.220 --> 00:30:47.670
than this and didn't focus
on photography solely,

00:30:47.670 --> 00:30:51.650
but really explores the different
aspects of East African migration

00:30:51.650 --> 00:30:55.450
and North African migration to
India to Persia to the Middle East

00:30:55.450 --> 00:30:57.600
and sort of social
mobility that was allowed.

00:30:57.600 --> 00:31:00.550
You know, people became
Generals, they became, you know,

00:31:00.550 --> 00:31:02.620
associated with royalty
and all the rest of it.

00:31:02.620 --> 00:31:08.770
So it wasn't - it's an interesting
series of stories that emerge.

00:31:08.770 --> 00:31:12.720
What's happening and this image is

00:31:12.720 --> 00:31:15.430
from what we can tell it's
possibly a celebration

00:31:15.430 --> 00:31:18.160
of Rosa Karney [phonic] which
